  const users = getUsersFromDB(); // future DB call
  const safeUsers = users.map(({ id, name }) => ({ id, name })); // drop email unless required
  res.json(safeUsers);
});
```

---

### 10. Hardcoded Port, No Environment Configuration (OWASP A05)

The port `3000` is hardcoded. Secrets, ports, and environment-specific settings should never be in source code.

```js
// ✅ Fix — use environment variables with sensible defaults
const PORT = parseInt(process.env.PORT, 10) || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT} [${process.env.NODE_ENV || 'development'}]`);
});
```

---

### 11. Missing Trust Proxy Configuration

If deployed behind a reverse proxy (nginx, AWS ALB), `req.ip` will return the proxy's IP instead of the real client IP, breaking rate limiting and audit logs.

```js
// ✅ Fix — set trust proxy appropriately for your infrastructure
app.set('trust proxy', 1); // trust first proxy hop (e.g., single load balancer)
```

---

### 12. No Request Body Size Limit (DoS Risk)

Without `express.json()` configured with a size limit, large payloads can exhaust memory.

```js
// ✅ Fix (already shown in #5 above)
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false, limit: '10kb' }));
```

---

## 🔵 LOW / INFORMATIONAL

### 13. `console.log` for Production Logging

`console.log` is synchronous and unstructured. Use a structured logger (see fix in #7) with log levels and log rotation/shipping for production.

### 14. No Dependency Vulnerability Scanning (OWASP A06)

No `package.json` with pinned dependency versions or a scanning step is present. Recommend running `npm audit` in CI and pinning dependency versions.

```bash
# Add to CI pipeline
npm audit --audit-level=high
npx snyk test
```

